  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>The imaging report is unambiguous. The pancreas is gone — surgically removed, confirmed on CT, no residual tissue. The patient is three months post-total pancreatectomy, now insulin-dependent, managing exocrine insufficiency with enzyme supplements, doing everything right. And at 3am, they wake with what they describe as a hot poker being turned in the upper abdomen, radiating through to the back, indistinguishable from the pain that drove them to surgery in the first place.</p>
  <p>This is not a rare complication. It is not a surgical error. It is not psychosomatic, and it is not drug-seeking behavior — a label that has followed pancreatitis patients through emergency departments for decades with the casual cruelty of institutional incuriosity. It is, according to the best available evidence, the predictable consequence of treating an organ when the disease has already moved to the brain.</p>
  <p>So where is the pain coming from? The pancreas is not there anymore.</p>
  <p>That question — deceptively simple, clinically devastating — is what the field of neuropancreatology has spent the last decade trying to answer. The answer it has arrived at is both mechanistically precise and institutionally damning: pancreatic pain is not a symptom of a sick organ. It is a disease of the nervous system that uses the pancreas as its origin point. And medicine, organized around the principle that you find the damaged structure and fix it, has been largely treating the wrong thing.</p>
</section>

<section id="three-mechanisms" class="reveal">
  <h2>Three Mechanisms, Not One Disease</h2>
  <p>Pancreatic pain is not a single phenomenon. Collapsing it into one category — 'abdominal pain from pancreatitis' — has been one of the field's more consequential errors, because it obscures the fact that three distinct mechanisms are operating, can coexist, and compound each other in ways that make any single-target intervention almost certain to fail in a meaningful proportion of patients.</p>
  <p>The first mechanism is visceral nociception from autodigestion. In acute pancreatitis, the inciting event — gallstones, alcohol metabolites, hyperlipidemia, or any of a dozen other triggers — causes cytosolic calcium overload in pancreatic acinar cells. Store-operated calcium entry (SOCE) channels are activated, and the resulting Ca²⁺ surge initiates the premature intracellular activation of digestive enzymes: trypsinogen converts to trypsin before it reaches the duodenum, and the pancreas begins digesting itself. The inflammatory cascade that follows is massive — acinar cell death via mitochondrial dysfunction and apoptosis, local tissue destruction, and systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) in the most severe cases. Pain signals travel via TRPV1 ion channels on primary sensory neurons, which release substance P and calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) into the spinal cord. A 2026 review in Signal Transduction and Targeted Therapy (Nature) confirmed that 80–95% of acute pancreatitis patients report severe upper abdominal pain as their initial complaint, often radiating to the back and worsening in the supine position.</p>
  <p>The autodigestion narrative is real. It is also incomplete. Roughly 80% of acute pancreatitis cases are mild and self-limiting — the enzyme cascade activates, inflammation occurs, and the system resolves without catastrophic progression. What determines whether a patient falls into the 25% who progress to severe disease, with a mortality rate of 30–40%, remains poorly understood. Enzyme activation alone does not explain it. The same 2026 review acknowledges that heterogeneity across etiologies remains a major barrier to predicting severity — which is part of why, despite knowing the calcium overload mechanism in granular molecular detail, we still cannot modify it pharmacologically.</p>
  <p>The second mechanism is peripheral neuropathic remodeling. In chronic pancreatitis — a progressive fibroinflammatory disease with a global incidence of approximately 10 cases per 100,000 person-years, twice as high in men as in women according to The Lancet's 2024 seminar — repeated inflammatory insults cause structural changes to the nerves themselves. Nerve hypertrophy. Increased nerve density within the pancreatic tissue. Peripheral sensitization, in which nociceptors lower their activation threshold and begin firing in response to stimuli that would not normally register as painful. A 2024 review in the Journal of Pancreatology (Walker et al.) noted that pain response to relief of ductal obstruction is incomplete in many patients, confirming that structural repair addresses only part of the pain architecture. TGFb1 and GP130 are emerging as potential biomarkers for distinguishing neuropathic from nociceptive pain in this population — but 'emerging' is doing a lot of work in that sentence. They are not clinically validated.</p>
  <p>The third mechanism is central sensitization. This is where the organ-pain relationship breaks down entirely.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Medicine has been treating the organ when the disease has moved to the brain. The patients who get no relief after total pancreatectomy are not outliers. They are the thesis."</p></aside>

<section id="central-sensitization" class="reveal">
  <h2>When the Brain Learns to Hurt Without the Organ</h2>
  <p>Central sensitization is the mechanism that makes the 3am hot poker possible after a total pancreatectomy. It is also the mechanism that medicine has been slowest to operationalize, because it is invisible on the imaging studies that drive clinical decision-making.</p>
  <p>Here is what happens. Substance P, released by sensory C fibers during repeated inflammatory episodes, drives hyperexcitability in the spinal dorsal horn. Over time, pain-processing circuits in the spinal cord and brain undergo synaptic reorganization — they become, in the most literal neurological sense, wired for pain. The circuits that were originally activated by peripheral injury from the pancreas begin to fire independently of any peripheral input. The original injury is no longer required. The nervous system has encoded the pain and is now running it on its own.</p>
  <p>A 2024 review in Life (MDPI) — 'Neuropancreatology: The Nervous System and Pain Management in Pancreatic Diseases' — put the clinical consequence of this plainly: central sensitization causes pain-related nervous system areas to remain active regardless of actual peripheral nerve activation. The evidence for this is not theoretical. It is the fact that total pancreatectomy fails to alleviate pain in up to 30% of chronic pancreatitis patients. The organ is gone. The pain is not. That 30% figure is the single most important clinical fact in this field, and it has not produced anything close to the institutional reckoning it deserves.</p>
  <p>The same review confirmed that substance P immunoreactivity correlates strongly with pain intensity, frequency, and duration in chronic pancreatitis — a finding that points directly at the neurochemical machinery of central sensitization and equally directly at the absence of any approved pharmacological agent that targets it in this context.</p>
  <p>There is a further complication. Pain severity in chronic pancreatitis does not reliably correlate with imaging findings or structural damage. A patient with extensive fibrosis and ductal dilation visible on MRI may report moderate pain. A patient with relatively preserved pancreatic architecture may be functionally disabled by it. This dissociation between structural pathology and pain experience is precisely what you would predict if central sensitization were driving a significant portion of the pain burden — but it also means that the diagnostic tools clinicians rely on are measuring the wrong thing.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Three-Mechanism Architecture of Pancreatic Pain</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Visceral Nociception (Autodigestion):</strong> Ca²⁺ overload via SOCE channels → premature trypsinogen activation → autodigestion → TRPV1-mediated substance P and CGRP release. Dominant in acute pancreatitis.</li>
    <li><strong>Peripheral Neuropathic Remodeling:</strong> Repeated inflammation → nerve hypertrophy, increased nerve density, lowered nociceptor thresholds. Dominant in chronic pancreatitis. Partially addressable by ductal decompression — but only partially.</li>
    <li><strong>Central Sensitization:</strong> Substance P-driven dorsal horn hyperexcitability → spinal and cortical pain circuits that fire independently of peripheral input. Explains why total pancreatectomy fails in up to 30% of chronic pancreatitis patients. No approved treatment targets this mechanism in pancreatitis.</li>
    <li><strong>Key clinical implication:</strong> These mechanisms coexist and compound. Treating only one — as most current interventions do — leaves the others intact.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="perineural-invasion" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Most Nerve-Invaded Cancer in the Human Body</h2>
  <p>Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) is a different disease from pancreatitis, with a different pain profile and a different underlying mechanism — and conflating them for narrative convenience would be a disservice to both. But in PDAC, the nervous system is not merely a bystander to the disease. It is an active participant in tumor spread, and the pain it produces is among the most intractable in oncology.</p>
  <p>Perineural invasion — PNI — is the process by which tumor cells physically invade along nerve sheaths, migrating through the perineural space that surrounds peripheral nerves. In most cancers, PNI is a concerning finding on pathology. In pancreatic cancer, it is essentially universal. A 2024 review in Frontiers in Oncology ('Hallmarks of perineural invasion in pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma') confirmed that PNI occurs in nearly 100% of PDAC cases, making it the most nerve-invaded cancer in the human body. That fact is extraordinary. It is also almost entirely unknown outside specialist oncology circles.</p>
  <p>The mechanism is not passive infiltration. Nerve growth factor (NGF) released in the tumor microenvironment interacts with TrkA receptors on sensory neurons, activating and sensitizing them. TRPV1 ion channels — the same channels implicated in acute pancreatitis pain — are upregulated, causing neurons to release CGRP and substance P into the central nervous system. Schwann cells and macrophages in the perineural space amplify pro-nociceptive signaling. The result is neurogenic inflammation that extends well beyond the tumor itself, and CNS pain regions that undergo synaptic reorganization in response to the sustained barrage of nociceptive input.</p>
  <p>PNI is not only a pain driver. The same Frontiers in Oncology review framed it as both a pain mechanism and a metastatic route — tumor cells using nerve sheaths as highways for spread, which is part of why it correlates negatively with survival. In 2024 alone, 66,440 new PDAC cases and 51,750 PDAC-related deaths were reported in the United States. Global PDAC cases more than doubled between 1990 and 2021, from approximately 207,905 to 508,533, with DALYs rising from 5.21 million to 11.32 million (GBD 2021, BMC Cancer, 2025).</p>
  <p>Pain affects approximately 90% of pancreatic cancer patients — a figure that tracks with the near-universal incidence of PNI, though the relationship is not perfectly causal. Some surgical cohorts report that only around 51% of patients present with pain at diagnosis, suggesting that perineural invasion does not always translate immediately into clinical pain experience. The relationship between nerve invasion and pain is more complex than a simple one-to-one model. What is not in dispute is that when PDAC pain becomes established, it is among the most difficult pain syndromes in medicine to manage — and that the WHO only classified chronic cancer pain as a distinct disease category in 2018, which tells you something about how long it took the field to take it seriously as a phenomenon in its own right.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"We know the calcium overload cascade. We know the SOCE channels. We know substance P and TRPV1. We know perineural invasion occurs in nearly 100% of pancreatic cancers. And we still have no approved treatment that modifies the disease. That gap is not a research problem. It is an institutional one."</p></aside>

<section id="therapeutic-vacuum" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Therapeutic Vacuum</h2>
  <p>Here is the state of play in 2026. Global pancreatitis cases rose 59% between 1990 and 2021, from 1.73 million to 2.75 million (GBD 2021, BMC Gastroenterology, 2024). In the United States, acute pancreatitis alone accounts for 275,000 hospital stays per year and $2.6 billion in annual healthcare costs (Frontiers in Molecular Neuroscience, 2023). Global acute pancreatitis incidence has increased at an average annual rate of 3% over recent decades. The molecular mechanisms of the disease — calcium overload, SOCE activation, TRPV1 signaling, substance P-driven central sensitization, NGF-TrkA-mediated perineural invasion — are understood in considerable detail.</p>
  <p>And there are no approved disease-modifying pharmacological treatments for either acute or chronic pancreatitis. None. A 2026 review in Frontiers in Physiology on targeted therapeutics concluded with the kind of sentence that should end careers and launch investigations: 'Despite improvements in supportive care and interventions, there are no approved disease-modifying pharmacologic or biologic therapies for AP or CP.' The same review identified a major barrier as heterogeneity across etiologies and difficulty in predicting severity — which is accurate, but also a description of a field that has not yet solved its basic translational problems despite decades of mechanistic research.</p>
  <p>What patients get instead is supportive care: fluid resuscitation, nutritional support, endoscopic or surgical decompression where applicable, and opioids. Short-term pain relief from endoscopic therapy (ESWL) for chronic pancreatitis is reported in around 85% of patients, but long-term improvements are seen in only about two-thirds (Frontiers in Physiology, 2025). For the remainder, and for those whose pain has become centrally maintained, the options narrow rapidly.</p>
  <p>The opioid question deserves direct treatment, because it is not a fringe concern. Opioids are the standard of care for pancreatitis pain. They are also, based on animal evidence, potentially counterproductive. Some studies suggest opioids may worsen disease severity through effects on the sphincter of Oddi — increasing biliary and pancreatic ductal pressure — and through disruption of intestinal motility. This has not been definitively established in human clinical trials, and the animal-to-human translation of sphincter of Oddi pharmacology is contested. But the concern is mechanistically plausible, and it sits unresolved at the center of standard clinical practice. Patients in severe pain are being given the one class of drugs that may, in some proportion of cases, be making the underlying disease worse. That is not a buried caveat. It is an unresolved clinical tension that the field has not adequately confronted.</p>
  <p>There is also the matter of what opioids do not do. They do not modify central sensitization. They do not reverse peripheral neuropathic remodeling. They do not inhibit NGF-TrkA signaling or reduce perineural invasion. They manage the symptom — imperfectly, with significant side effects, and with the well-documented risks of dependence — while leaving every underlying mechanism intact.</p>
</section>

<section id="genetics" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Nervous System You Were Born With</h2>
  <p>A 2024 study in the Journal of Pain — using genome-wide association study (GWAS) and transcriptome-wide association study (TWAS) analysis on the NAPS2 cohort of recurrent acute and chronic pancreatitis patients — identified multiple genetic risk variant pathways for severe and continuous pancreatitis pain. The variants implicated include those that increase local inflammation, potentiate BDNF-associated pain mechanisms, and alter nervous system development and connectivity.</p>
  <p>The conceptual shift this represents is significant. Pain severity in pancreatitis is not simply a function of how badly the pancreas is damaged. It is partly a function of the nervous system the patient was born with — its baseline connectivity, its BDNF signaling architecture, its predisposition toward central sensitization. Two patients with identical pancreatic pathology can have radically different pain experiences, and part of that difference may be written in their genome.</p>
  <p>The researchers concluded that 'the initial phase of recognizing the link between pathologic pancreatic pain experience and genetic variants in neuronal genes in the brain, spinal cord and peripheral nervous system is a major step forward.' They are right. It is also worth being precise about what the NAPS2 findings are and are not. The study used candidate gene approaches with known limitations in statistical power. The clinical utility of genotyping for pancreatitis pain management is not validated. Genotyping pancreatitis patients to guide pain treatment is not something any clinician can currently do in a meaningful way. The finding is a conceptual advance, not a clinical tool — and the distance between those two things, in this field, has a way of being longer than it looks.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Diagnostic and Therapeutic Gap at a Glance</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Approved disease-modifying treatments for acute pancreatitis:</strong> Zero (Frontiers in Physiology, 2026)</li>
    <li><strong>Approved disease-modifying treatments for chronic pancreatitis:</strong> Zero (Frontiers in Physiology, 2026)</li>
    <li><strong>Total pancreatectomy failure rate for pain relief in CP:</strong> Up to 30% (Life/MDPI, 2024)</li>
    <li><strong>PNI incidence in pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma:</strong> ~100% (Frontiers in Oncology, 2024)</li>
    <li><strong>Validated biomarkers to distinguish peripheral vs. centrally maintained pain:</strong> None in clinical use</li>
    <li><strong>Long-term pain relief from endoscopic therapy (ESWL) in CP:</strong> ~67% (Frontiers in Physiology, 2025)</li>
    <li><strong>Annual US healthcare cost of acute pancreatitis:</strong> $2.6 billion (Frontiers in Molecular Neuroscience, 2023)</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-central-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Wrong Model, Applied Consistently</h2>
  <p>The central sensitization problem in pancreatic pain is not an anomaly. It is an extreme case of something that happens across chronic pain conditions — fibromyalgia, complex regional pain syndrome, chronic low back pain, post-surgical pain syndromes — where the nervous system learns pain, encodes it, and eventually runs it independently of the original injury. What makes pancreatic pain distinctive is the clarity of the demonstration. You can remove the organ. You can confirm its absence on imaging. And in up to 30% of patients, the pain continues, unchanged, because the organ was never really the source of the pain by that point. The nervous system was.</p>
  <p>Medicine's organ-centric model — find the damaged structure, fix or remove it, pain resolves — is not wrong as a general principle. It works for a great many conditions. But it breaks down completely in the face of central sensitization, and the field has been slow to update its diagnostic and therapeutic frameworks accordingly. The patients who get no relief after total pancreatectomy are not outliers or diagnostic puzzles. They are the clearest possible demonstration that the model was wrong — and that the consequences of applying a wrong model to people in severe pain are not abstract.</p>
  <p>There is also no validated clinical tool to identify, before surgery, which patients are likely to fall into that 30%. There are no biomarkers that reliably distinguish patients whose pain is primarily peripheral — and thus potentially amenable to local intervention — from those whose pain has become centrally maintained. TGFb1 and GP130 are being investigated. The NAPS2 genetic architecture is being mapped. These are genuine advances. They are not yet clinical realities.</p>
  <p>Walker et al., writing in the Journal of Pancreatology in 2024, noted that 'there still remains much to discover about the neural regulation of pancreas-related pain' and that many therapeutic options 'provide incomplete relief.' That is a careful, accurate, and quietly devastating summary of where the field stands. Patients described their pain to clinicians using words — 'burning, ripping, bursting, stabbing, relentless, crushing, jolting, electric-shock, hot poker' — that are indistinguishable from descriptions of neuropathic pain syndromes. The language was there. The diagnostic framework to act on it was not.</p>
  <p>Recognizing pancreatic pain as a disease of the nervous system, not just the organ, is, as the NAPS2 researchers put it, a major step forward. It is also, quietly, an indictment of how long it took us to get here — and of what was done, and not done, to the patients who were in pain while we were still looking at the wrong organ.</p>
</section>

